# Sales & Marketing Efficiency KPIs

Metrics that measure the effectiveness and cost-efficiency of client acquisition processes.

## Core Metrics

| KPI | Definition | Formula / Method | Target / Benchmark | Category |
|-----|------------|------------------|-------------------|----------|
| **MQLs (Marketing Qualified Leads)** | Leads showing interest/intent based on engagement signals | Count of leads meeting MQL criteria | — | Top of Funnel |
| **SQLs (Sales Qualified Leads)** | Prospects with fit, need, and budget verified by sales | Count of leads passing sales qualification | — | Pipeline Quality |
| **New Proposals Sent** | Number of formal proposals issued | Count of proposals delivered | — | Sales Activity |
| **Win Rate (%)** | Percentage of proposals that convert to deals | Deals Won ÷ Proposals Sent × 100 | **30-60%** (varies by model) | Conversion |
| **Average Deal Size ($)** | Average value of closed deals | Total New Client Value ÷ Number of Deals | — | Deal Quality |
| **Sales Cycle Length (Days)** | Average time from first contact to close | Average days from lead creation to deal close | — | Sales Velocity |
| **Customer Acquisition Cost (CAC)** | Total sales + marketing cost per new client acquired | (Total Sales + Marketing Costs) ÷ New Clients | **$4K-6K typical** | Efficiency |
| **CAC Payback Period (Months)** | Time to recover acquisition investment | CAC ÷ Monthly Gross Profit from New Client | **< 6 months** | Cash Efficiency |
| **LTV:CAC Ratio (3-Month)** | Lifetime value relative to acquisition cost (3-month window) | (Avg Client LTV) ÷ CAC | **> 3:1** | Unit Economics |
| **LTV:CAC Ratio (6-Month)** | Lifetime value relative to acquisition cost (6-month window) | (Avg Client LTV) ÷ CAC | **> 3:1** | Unit Economics |

## Conversion Funnel Logic

### MQL → SQL → Proposal → Win

**Healthy conversion rates:**
- MQL to SQL: ≥ 25%
- SQL to Proposal: ≥ 60%
- Proposal to Win: 30-60% (model-dependent)

**Warning signs:**
- High MQLs but flat SQLs = targeting or qualification issue
- High SQLs but low win rate = positioning or pricing issue
- Long sales cycles without deal size increase = friction in buying process

## CAC & LTV Economics

### CAC Components
- Marketing spend (ads, content, events, tools)
- Sales salaries and commissions
- Sales operations and enablement costs

### LTV Calculation
- Average monthly client value × average client lifetime (months)
- Should factor in gross margin, not gross revenue

### Efficiency Benchmarks

| Metric | Healthy Range | Warning Zone | Critical |
|--------|---------------|--------------|----------|
| **LTV:CAC** | > 3:1 | 2:1 to 3:1 | < 2:1 |
| **CAC Payback** | < 6 months | 6-12 months | > 12 months |
| **Win Rate** | 40-60% | 25-40% | < 25% |

## Key Relationships

### MQLs → SQLs → Win Rate → CAC
- Quality of top-of-funnel leads affects conversion efficiency
- Better targeting reduces wasted sales cycles
- Higher win rates naturally reduce CAC per closed deal

### Deal Size ↔ Sales Cycle
- Larger deals typically extend sales cycles
- Evaluate these metrics together — longer cycles acceptable if deal value justifies

### CAC → Payback → LTV:CAC
- These form the financial efficiency loop of acquisition
- Rising CAC without corresponding LTV growth shrinks cash runway
- Efficient CAC with strong LTV creates self-funding growth

## Rules of Thumb

### Sales & Marketing Efficiency Rules
- LTV:CAC ≥ 3:1
- CAC payback ≤ 6 months
- Win rate ≥ 30% (varies by agency type)
- SQL volume sufficient for 4-6 months pipeline

### Warning Signs
- CAC rising faster than LTV
- Payback period extending beyond 9 months
- Win rate declining for 2+ quarters
- MQL volume high but SQL conversion low

## Interpretation Notes

- **Rising MQLs** = growing awareness and effective content
- **Improving win rate** = better positioning or qualification
- **Increasing deal size** = pricing power and value perception
- **Shorter sales cycle** = reduced friction and stronger authority
- **Declining CAC** = improved targeting or organic momentum

