# Productivity & Capacity KPIs

Metrics that measure how efficiently the agency converts human effort into revenue and profit.

## Core Metrics

| KPI | Definition | Formula / Method | Target / Benchmark | Category |
|-----|------------|------------------|-------------------|----------|
| **Billable Utilization Rate (%)** | Percentage of available time spent on billable client work | (Billable Hours ÷ Available Hours) × 100 | **> 70%** | Efficiency |
| **Fully Billable Staff** | Percentage of team that is 80%+ billable | (80%+ Billable Staff ÷ Total Staff) × 100 | **≥ 80%** | Team Structure |
| **Billable Hours Available (#)** | Total hours team could bill per month | Sum of all available work hours | — | Capacity |
| **Hours Billed (#)** | Hours actually billed to clients | Sum of invoiced hours | — | Productivity |
| **Unbilled Hours (#)** | Available hours not invoiced (inefficiency) | Available Hours - Billed Hours | **Keep minimal** | Leakage |
| **Target Hourly Rate** | Agency's target billable rate per hour | Total AGI ÷ Total Billable Hours | **$200/hr benchmark** | Pricing |
| **Billable : Non-Billable Ratio** | Ratio of revenue-generating to support staff | Billable FTEs ÷ Non-Billable FTEs | **3:1** | Leverage |
| **AGI per FTE** | Agency Gross Income per full-time employee | Total AGI ÷ Total FTEs | **> $15,500/month** ($186K/year) | Productivity |
| **ARPE (Average Revenue per Employee)** | Total revenue per employee (includes pass-throughs) | Total Revenue ÷ Total FTEs | **$250K-300K/year** (model dependent) | Scale |
| **Project Profitability (%)** | Margin per project after direct costs | (Project Revenue - Direct Costs) ÷ Project Revenue × 100 | **20-30%** | Margin Control |
| **Overtime / Overcapacity Hours (%)** | Percentage of hours worked beyond standard capacity | Overtime Hours ÷ Total Hours × 100 | **< 5-10%** | Sustainability |

## AGI per FTE: The Critical Leverage Metric

### Healthy Ranges by Stage

| Agency Maturity | AGI per FTE Target | Monthly Equivalent |
|-----------------|-------------------|-------------------|
| **Early-stage (≤$1M AGI)** | $140K-$160K/year | $11.7K-$13.3K/month |
| **Mid-stage ($2-5M AGI)** | $160K-$180K/year | $13.3K-$15K/month |
| **Scalable ($5-10M AGI)** | $180K-$200K/year | $15K-$16.7K/month |
| **Elite (Operationally Mature)** | $200K-$225K/year | $16.7K-$18.8K/month |

### What AGI per FTE Measures

**Not just:**
- How hard people work
- Raw output volume

**But rather:**
- How efficiently the business converts time into economic value
- Quality of pricing, systems, and role clarity
- True operational leverage

### Revenue per FTE vs. AGI per FTE

**Critical Distinction:**

| Metric | Includes | Best For |
|--------|----------|----------|
| **Revenue per FTE** | All billing including pass-throughs | External benchmarking, topline comparison |
| **AGI per FTE** | Only value agency keeps (minus passthroughs) | Operational efficiency, profit analysis, valuation |

**Typical relationship:**
- Media agencies: Revenue per FTE might be $350K but AGI per FTE only $150K
- Strategic agencies: Revenue per FTE $250K and AGI per FTE $220K

**Always use AGI per FTE for efficiency and profitability analysis.**

## Utilization & Capacity Balance

### Utilization Sweet Spots

| Range | Interpretation | Action |
|-------|----------------|--------|
| **< 60%** | Undercapacity or overstaffing | Review forecast, consider strategic hiring pause |
| **60-70%** | Healthy buffer for growth and innovation | Maintain; allows internal projects |
| **70-80%** | Optimal productive range | Sustainable high performance |
| **80-90%** | High output but monitor sustainability | Watch for early burnout signals |
| **> 90%** | Overcapacity risk zone | High burnout risk; quality may suffer |

### Billable : Non-Billable Ratio

**Healthy progression:**
- Early stage: 2:1 (building support infrastructure)
- Mid-stage: 3:1 (balanced leverage)
- Mature: 3:1 to 4:1 (optimized operations)

**Warning:** Ratios above 5:1 often indicate under-investment in infrastructure.

## Key Relationships

### Utilization → AGI per FTE → Profit
- Higher utilization increases AGI per person
- But only sustainable if systems support the workload
- Pushing beyond 85% usually reduces quality and increases burnout

### AGI per FTE → Forecast Accuracy → Hiring Decisions
- Stable AGI per FTE enables confident hiring predictions
- Declining AGI per FTE signals overhiring or underforecasting
- Use as early-warning indicator of structural inefficiency

### Project Profitability → EBITDA
- Each project's margin compounds into agency-level profit
- Target 20-30% project margin to sustain 30-35% EBITDA
- Margin leakage at project level is often invisible until too late

## Rules of Thumb

### Productivity Rules
- Utilization ≥ 70%
- Billable:Non-Billable ratio ≥ 3:1
- AGI per FTE ≥ $15.5K/month
- Project profitability ≥ 20%
- Unbilled time < 5%
- Overtime < 5-10%

### Warning Signs
- AGI per FTE declining for 2+ quarters
- Utilization consistently > 90%
- Unbilled hours increasing
- Project profitability < 15%
- Rising overtime trends

## Interpretation Notes

- **Rising AGI per FTE** = improved leverage, pricing power, or efficiency
- **High utilization with low burnout** = healthy systems and role clarity
- **Strong project profitability** = good scoping and delivery control
- **Minimal unbilled hours** = strong capacity planning and accountability
- **Consistent metrics** = operational predictability and scalability

